  "tour": [
    {
      "order": 1,
      "title": "Project Intent & Manifesto",
      "description": "Start with the canonical project pitch. README.md is the 5.5K-line overview that frames RuVector as a self-learning vector + graph + LLM operating system (GNN that learns from queries, SONA self-optimizer, DiskANN, ColBERT, Matryoshka, hybrid sparse+dense, Cypher, local LLMs). CLAUDE.md is the in-repo playbook for agents working in the tree, and CHANGELOG.md captures what has actually shipped through the 0.1.x and hailo-backend releases \u2014 together they tell you what the workstation install is supposed to deliver and at what maturity.",
      "nodeIds": [
        "document:README.md",
        "document:CLAUDE.md",
        "document:CHANGELOG.md"
      ]
    },
    {
      "order": 2,
      "title": "The Installer's Contract",
      "description": "`install.sh` is the user-facing front door this slice is about: a one-line bootstrap that installs Rust via rustup if missing, then runs `cargo install ruvector-cli` (producing the Rust binaries) plus `npm install -g ruvector` (the JS wrapper). The Cargo workspace manifest declares which member crates exist and the shared dependency versions, so reading the two together tells you exactly which artifacts land on disk and from where.",
      "nodeIds": [
        "file:install.sh",
        "config:Cargo.toml"
      ],
      "languageLesson": "Cargo workspaces let multiple crates share one Cargo.lock and one target/ directory. `cargo install <crate>` reads the crate's [[bin]] entries from its own Cargo.toml and compiles each as a standalone binary into ~/.cargo/bin \u2014 that's how a single workspace publishes both `ruvector` and `ruvector-mcp-server`."
    },
    {
      "order": 3,
      "title": "What `cargo install ruvector-cli` Actually Builds",
      "description": "The ruvector-cli crate manifest is the precise specification of what gets compiled and installed. It declares two binaries \u2014 `ruvector` and `ruvector-mcp-server` \u2014 pulls in ~60 dependencies (clap, tokio, sqlx, axum, indicatif), and gates optional features. After this step you can predict exactly which executables show up in `~/.cargo/bin` and what optional capabilities the build can toggle.",
      "nodeIds": [
        "config:crates/ruvector-cli/Cargo.toml",
        "document:crates/ruvector-cli/README.md"
      ],
      "languageLesson": "Cargo `[[bin]]` tables are how one crate publishes multiple binaries; each entry maps a name to a `path` source file. Feature flags in `[features]` let downstream installers opt into heavier code paths (e.g. postgres, hailo) without bloating the default build."
    },
    {
      "order": 4,
      "title": "Binary Entry Point & Command Dispatch",
      "description": "`main.rs` is the literal entry point of the `ruvector` binary you just installed: it defines the top-level clap Cli/Commands enum and dispatches every subcommand to a handler in the `cli/` module. `config.rs` is the very first thing those handlers consult \u2014 a hierarchical Config / DatabaseConfig / CliConfig / McpConfig loaded from TOML and overridden by env vars. Together they answer 'when I type `ruvector \u2026`, what runs and how does it find its settings?'",
      "nodeIds": [
        "file:crates/ruvector-cli/src/main.rs",
        "file:crates/ruvector-cli/src/config.rs",
        "file:crates/ruvector-cli/src/cli/mod.rs"
      ],
      "languageLesson": "Clap's derive API turns a Rust enum into a full argument parser at compile time: each variant becomes a subcommand and its fields become named flags. The dispatcher is a single `match` on the enum \u2014 adding a verb means adding a variant and one match arm, nothing more."
    },
    {
      "order": 5,
      "title": "The CLI Command Surface \u2014 What You'll Actually Type",
      "description": "These modules implement the verbs a user runs after install. `commands.rs` owns the core vector-DB ops (create, insert, search, info, benchmark, export, import) including JSON/CSV/NPY ingestion. `graph.rs` adds the Cypher subcommands and an embedded HTTP/gRPC/GraphQL server. `format.rs` and `progress.rs` are the shared output layer (colored tables, JSON/CSV dumps, indicatif progress bars). Read this step to know which commands actually exist on the binary that just landed in your PATH.",
      "nodeIds": [
        "file:crates/ruvector-cli/src/cli/commands.rs",
